@startuml task-retry-race
' AgentTask retry: the currentPodUID gate, and the two races that both yield 403 StalePodCompletion.
' Source of truth: docs/src/controller/task-lifecycle.md
!include _style.puml

participant "AgentTask\nReconciler" as R $ctrlBg
participant "AgentTask\nstatus" as S $mutedBg
participant "{taskName}-completion\nConfigMap" as CM $storeBg
participant "Gateway" as G $gwBg
participant "Old Pod" as OP $agentBg
participant "New Pod" as NP $agentBg

R -> S : 1. increment status.retries

group #FFE4E1 gate closed: no Pod can write a completion
  R -> S : 2. currentPodUID = ""
  R -> OP : 3. delete Pod
  OP ->> G : late in-flight\n/v1/task/complete
  G -->> OP : 403 StalePodCompletion
  note over G, OP
    Step 2's security purpose: the
    old Pod's result can no longer
    overwrite the retry's data.
  end note

  R -> CM : 4. patch back to data: {}
  note over R, CM
    Patched, not deleted, so the
    ownerRef and the gateway's
    name-scoped update/patch Role
    stay valid. Order matters:
    clearing the UID (2) must
    precede the reset (4), or the
    old Pod could refill the
    emptied mailbox.
  end note

  R -> NP : 5-6. PVC retained, phase=Provisioning,\ncreate the new Pod
  NP ->> G : first /v1/task/complete,\nracing the stamp
  G -->> NP : 403 StalePodCompletion
end

NP --> R : 7. informer reports the new Pod
R -> S : 7. currentPodUID = newPod.UID\nGATE RE-OPENS

NP -> G : /v1/task/complete
G -> CM : write the result

note over NP, G
  The second 403 is benign and
  retryable: the informer-lag
  window is typically under 100ms
  against seconds of agent startup,
  and agents retry on
  StalePodCompletion per the
  runtime contract. Same status
  code, opposite cause: one rejects
  a stale writer, the other a
  writer that is merely early.
end note

@enduml
